Alcoa ( AA ) suffered due to low aluminum prices in 2013, but has performed better than 2012 in the first three quarters due to cost-cutting efforts and the contribution from the value-added product divisions. In the first nine months of 2013, Alcoa recorded revenues of $17.4 billion compared to $17.8 billion in the comparable period of 2012. Despite lower revenues, net income stood at $54 million compared to a net loss of $95 million last year due to cost related savings.

In the first nine months of the year, the company recorded revenues of $13.1 billion as compared to $14.8 billion in the comparable period last year. While this was primarily due to a goodwill impairment worth $1.8 billion, the quantum of loss would have been greater than 2012 even otherwise. Things haven't really improved in the fourth quarter so we expect U.S. Steel to end up with a poorer overall performance compared to 2012.

For example, some investors may believe that Apple (NASDAQ: AAPL ) is expensive because it trades for over $586 a share. Gold Continues to Rise as Greece Bailout Package Bolsters Euro. Gold is continuing to rise to reach a four-month high in morning trade Monday, as Greece secured a financial aid package totaling up to 45 billion euros, or about $61 billion, from European governments as well as the International Monetary Fund. Specifically, the euro zone mininsters agreed over the weekend to provide up to 30 billion euros, while the remaining 15 billion euros will come from the IMF.

The DJIA's Dangerous Indexing Philosophy. While doing some research on the Dow Jones Industrial Average, I was disappointed to discover how skewed it is toward just a few of its components and how dangerous it is for the world to use it as a benchmark for the American markets. The DJIA is a price weighted index, which simply means that the weighting of the index is based on the price of each component.
